s quick reference to find the right accounts.\n\n\n\nYour Goal\nFollow These Influencers\n\n\n\n\nLearn SEO fundamentals\nNeil Patel, Nathan Gotch, Moz, Sam Oh, Tommy Griffith\n\n\nBuild an SEO agency\nRyan Stewart, Craig Campbell, Matt Diggity, Joshua George\n\n\nGrow a local business\nJoy Hawkins, Darren Shaw, Greg Gifford, Ben Fisher, Carolyn Lyden\n\n\nB2B marketing and SEO\nRoss Simmonds, John Bonini, Dharmesh Shah, HubSpot, Mike King\n\n\nContent marketing strategy\nBrendan Hufford, Amanda Natividad, Gael Breton, Spencer Haws\n\n\nTechnical SEO\nAreej AbuAli, Lily Ray, Mark Williams-Cook, Mike King, Britney Muller\n\n\nE-commerce SEO\nErik Huberman, Rachel Pedersen, Kim Garst\n\n\nSaaS and startup SEO\nKevin Indig, Eli Schwartz, Brendan Hufford, Rand Fishkin\n\n\nLink building\nBrian Dean, Robbie Richards, Kasra Dash, Charles Floate, James Dooley\n\n\nGoogle algorithm updates\nLily Ray, Marie Haynes, Barry Schwartz, Brodie Clark, Danny Sullivan\n\n\nNiche site building\nSpencer Haws, Carl Broadbent, Doug Cunnington, Adam Enfroy, Gael Breton\n\n\nFree SEO education\nH-Educate, Chase Reiner, Ahrefs, Moz, Semrush\n\n\n\n\nBuild your blog. Skip the busywork. Stacc writes and publishes SEO content for you.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nUnderstanding engagement rates helps you evaluate which influencers actually reach their audience. Inflated follower counts mean nothing without engagement. These benchmarks help you judge real influence.\n\n\n\nFollower Tier\nAverage Engagement Rate\nBest Content Format\n\n\n\n\nNano (1K-10K)\n5.2%\nCarousel posts\n\n\nMicro (10K-100K)\n3.86%\nReels + Carousels\n\n\nMid (100K-500K)\n2.3%\nReels\n\n\nMacro (500K+)\n1.2%\nShort-form video\n\n\n\nReels average 1.23% engagement across all account sizes. That is the best-performing format on Instagram in 2026. Carousels are a close second at approximately 1.1%.\nFor SEO influencers, carousel posts tend to outperform Reels. The content is educational and requires time to absorb. A 10-slide carousel breaking down a keyword research process holds attention longer than a 30-second Reel.\nThe takeaway is simple. Do not judge SEO influencers by follower count alone. A 10K account with 5% engagement reaches 500 engaged people per post. A 500K account with 1% engagement reaches 5,000 people per post. The larger account has more raw reach. But the smaller account has 5 times the engagement density.\n\nInstagram is not the first platform most people associate with SEO education. Twitter/X, LinkedIn, and YouTube dominate that space. But Instagram reaches a different audience entirely.\nBrands earn an average of $5.78 for every dollar spent on influencer marketing. SEO professionals who follow influencers on Instagram stay current with algorithm updates before those updates become blog posts. Visual summaries and carousels condense complex concepts into 2-minute reads.\nFor business owners, following these accounts serves 3 purposes:\n\nStay current. Algorithm updates and tool launches appear on Instagram before formal announcements.\nLearn visually. Carousel posts condense complex SEO concepts into 10 slides.\nBuild relationships. Engaging with SEO influencers opens doors for link building and collaboration.\n\nThe SEO influencers who post on Instagram are not simplifying their content. They are reformatting it. A 10-slide carousel can deliver the same information as a 2,000-word blog post. The medium is different. The insights are the same.\nThe SEO community on Instagram is smaller than Twitter or LinkedIn. That makes it easier to get noticed and build real connections. Comment on posts. Share carousels. Tag people. DM with genuine questions. The algorithm rewards engagement, and smaller communities reward participation.\nFor more SEO learning resources, check our guides on the best SEO YouTube channels, best SEO influencers on LinkedIn, best SEO blogs, and best SEO newsletters.\n\nWho is the most-followed SEO influencer on Instagram?\nNeil Patel is the most-fo